							<p>
								Welcome to <a href="https://blair.pictures/">blair.pictures</a>!
								This is the first WordPress site I‚Äôve developed on my own. Until
								now, I‚Äôve mostly made static sites like
								<a href="https://jekyllrb.com/">Jekyll</a> or
								<a href="https://www.gatsbyjs.org/">Gatsby</a>. These frameworks
								offer a self-contained environment that can be run entirely
								through the terminal, which I‚Äôve always found easier to wrap my
								head around. I didn‚Äôt want to lose that with this site, so I
								created this (janky) setup to work around it!
							</p>
							<h2>Why use WordPress?</h2>
							<p>
								So why would I use WordPress if I like the toolchains of static
								sites so much? It really came down to images. Basically, the way
								you manage content on a static site is by committing files
								directly to a Git repository. This is fine for text-heavy sites,
								but it‚Äôs not great for sites like this that use lots of images.
								Your choices are to commit large, binary files to your git
								repo‚Äîwhich will quickly inflate its size‚Äîor to figure out another
								way of hosting these images.
							</p>
							<p>
								Though there are some options available, most of the easy-to-use
								solutions like Contentful, were fairly expensive. Meanwhile
								Dreamhost offered an inexpensive WordPress Hosting plan with
								unlimited storage. On top of that I would have an environment that
								I could access from several devices, which is really helpful since
								I do a lot of my drawing on my iPad. So with all those factors
								considered, I decided to bite the bullet and make a WordPress
								site!
							</p>
							<h2>Creating an Isolate Environment with Docker</h2>
							<p>
								With WordPress selected, I needed to figure out my local
								development environment. I always found this part intimidating.
								Unlike with a static site, where all you have to do is download
								some files and run some commands on the terminal, with WordPress
								you needto set up an entire LAMP stack! Tools like MAMP make
								easier, but I would always worried I‚Äôd leave some process running
								in the background, or I‚Äôd have trouble resetting the database. I
								wanted to be able to launch and teardown my environment easily.
							</p>
							<p>
								The tool I ended up turning to was Docker. I‚Äôve been using it a
								lot at work recently, and I liked its ability to create isolated,
								composable environments. Even better, there was already a
								WordPress Docker image, so creating an environment was as simple
								as creating a docker-compose.yaml file!
							</p>
							<p>
								Still, some of the functionality I wanted was a little verbose,
								and there were some gotchas‚Äîlike how to completely reset the
								database. To make these common functions a little easier to
								remember, I created some npm run scripts to simplify things:
							</p>
							<ul>
								<li>
									<code>launch</code> ‚Äì Setup the docker container using
									docker-compose
								</li>
								<li>
									<code>stop</code> ‚Äì Stop running the docker container (but leave
									everything in-tact)
								</li>
								<li>
									<code>teardown</code> ‚Äì Stop and remove all volumes associated
									with the site. Useful in case things get too out-of-hand and you
									want to start from scratch
								</li>
								<li>
									<code>ssh</code> ‚Äì Essentially just executes bash inside the
									docker container. Useful for when you want to explore the file
									system inside the image
								</li>
							</ul>
							<p>
								With these, I was able to create an isolated WordPress environment
								that I could setup and teardown at will!
							</p>
							<h2>Setting Up Live Development</h2>
							<p>
								The next thing I needed to figure out was how to make changes to
								the site. My solution was to create 2 folders at the root of the
								environment, plugins and themes. The contents of these folders are
								.gitignored, so I could just git clone existing themes and plugins
								into them. Then, I created a new npm run script to copy those
								files into the container:
							</p>
							<ul>
								<li>
									<code>build</code> ‚Äì copies the contents of plugins and themes
									into the appropriate location in the Docker container
								</li>
